article.description: Jameer Nelson scored a season-high 25 points to lead Orlando to a 107-87 win over Minnesota.
article.headline: Nelson scores 25 points in Magic win over Wolves
article.linkText: Full Nelson: Jameer nets 25 as Magic beat Wolves
article.story: ORLANDO (AP) -- Orlando Magic coach Brian Hill knows his team's three-game winning streak is just the nature of the NBA. The Magic beat the Minnesota Timberwolves 107-87 on Friday night, ending a six-game homestand 3-3. Orlando had lost nine of its last 11 before its current winning streak. "It's funny how this league goes," Hill said. "I think if you look at the whole league from the beginning of the year until now, there have probably been six or eight teams that have gone through what we're going through. "I can't really explain it but I'm just happy about the fact that we finished out really well these last three games and there's no reason why we can't go on the road and play the same type of basketball." Jameer Nelson scored a season-high 25 points to lead Orlando, which begins a three-game road trip Jan. 3 at Detroit. Steve Francis added 21 points and Grant Hill 17. Dwight Howard had 17 points and 12 rebounds for his 20th double-double of the season. "I think we're playing a little bit better, a little more as a team, as opposed to going one-on-one and really just trying to put the team on your back," Nelson said. Kevin Garnett led the Timberwolves with 29 points and Wally Szczerbiak added 24. Orlando's bench outscored Minnesota 40-13 and the Magic held a 42-25 rebounding advantage. "We didn't play the game the right way," Szczerbiak said. "They went on a run, they stayed aggressive. That team's playing better. They're a lot better than their record. No question about it." The Magic built a 21-point lead in the second quarter, but Minnesota battled back to take a 67-66 lead at 5:47 of the third quarter on Marko Jaric's jumper. Steve Francis tied the game with a free throw that started a 13-5 run for the Magic. He hit five free throws during that stretch to help the Magic finish the quarter with a 79-72 lead. Orlando scored the first seven points of the fourth quarter to put the game away. "That's the biggest thing we've got to learn when teams make their push, we've got to push back and not sulk or anything," Howard said. "And I think for the most part we did that." Orlando led 57-37 with 3:27 remaining in the first half but Minnesota outscored the Magic 14-2 the rest of the way to close to 59-51 at the break. Garnett had six of his 17 points during the run and Trenton Hassell hit a 3-pointer at the buzzer. Orlando, which shot 55.8 percent in the first half, was led by Nelson and Francis with 12 points each. ^Notes:@ Minnesota assistant Johnny Davis made his first trip back to Orlando since serving as the Magic head coach last season. Davis was fired with 18 games remaining after going 31-33. Orlando's Kelvin Cato did not dress after playing the last two games. Cato was on the inactive list from Dec. 7-26 with a sprained right ankle. Orlando's Mario Kasun had five fouls in just 8:47. Minnesota blocked eight shots, including three by Garnett. Orlando hit 14 of 16 free throws in the second half.
